<date>1512122111456<//date><resp>None<//resp><name>Zachary Sturgeon</name>< Text>
I got the thai basil gimlet to drink, the seafood hot and sweet basil as an entree, and the fried calamari as an appetizer. I seriously love basil, and all the dishes delivered! Everything was amazing. The calamari, served with a sweet dipping sauce and carrots fried in the same manner, was perfectly crunchy while being light on the batter and oil; it was seriously perfect, I can't say I've had better! The seafood basil entree was perfect too! It came with all varieties of seafood; white fish, shrimp, clam, and a mussel, served with basil and sliced peppers. The sauce absolutely delivered on the name, being spicy and sweet, salty with a hint of brown sugar. I poured my rice in to the bowl and ate it all up. I ate the salad last, lettuce and carrot in a sweet clear dressing. The drink was heavy on the basil, sweet and savory, I'm not one to describe alcohol well but it hit the spot! I'll be back before I leave town for sure!</Text>

<userid>102272456959463623610</userid><Name>Steven Suarez</Name><Time>1533051419798<//Time>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< review>
I went to this place on a whim and I walked out a very, very satisfied and happy customer.

In terms of decorations, there is not a lot, but what it does use gives the place a very unique atmosphere. It's not overly bright, not is it too dark. If you so wish, they offer seating outside as well.

The food here was absolutely amazing! Let's start with the strawberry lemonade. Not only was it tasty, citrusy, and very refreshing, but it was also refillable for free! That alone is awesome, but then I was served my food and I almost forgot about the lemonade because I was met with an explosion of flavors from every item on plate. Explosion may conjure a sense of really strong and overpowering tatstes. That was not the case here. Everything blended together in harmony accentuating what makes each ingredient unique. The sticky rice went so well with the sauce that they provided.

If you want to go on a journey of flavors, this place is for you and you can rest assure knowing that the service is just as good.</review>

< UserId.>
111234090731148061664< /UserId.>
< Name>
Katherine Phillips< /Name>
<date>1572045021883</date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
This is a nice little place down the street from the Warner theater my friend and I visited.

The wait staff was incredible and if I had more money to give as a tip I would have given more.

I ordered the green curry, added bamboo shoots and asked for it to be spicy.

They brought out the curry in this beautifully exotic bowl that looked a bit like a tiny bathtub. It was green as advertised and when I tasted my first spoonful an explosion of flavor and spice graced my tongue. The eggplant was moist and acted like a delicate sponge. The bamboo shoots were fantastically crunchy and the bell peppers brought a fantastic yet brief relief from the spice.

She brought me a side of Jasmine rice (my favorite) and adding the curry to that made the experience even more delightful.

Keep doing what you're doing Baramee you have a good thing going.<//Review>

< Text>
The silkiest, most beautiful tasting tokontsu (pork) broth I‚Äôve ever had. Their white original is my go to. Great noodle texture, tender chashu. Excellent gyoza, hot off the grill, decent chasu bowls. It would be almost perfect if the service wasn‚Äôt so awful. It is such a hit and miss with their service, but my past two visits (with months between them) were unsatisfying. The most recent time, it took way too long to receive our food after ordering. My boyfriend‚Äôs ramen arrived before our chashu bowls, gyoza, and even before my drink, which I had to inquire about. It took less than 3 seconds for my drink to be placed on my table - why wouldn‚Äôt the server have just done that in the first place? It seems that they are understaffed and one server puts more effort into their job than the other. Even now, finished with our food, we needed to flag our server down to give them our payment. It took the duration of our meal for the table next to us to even have their order taken! I would like to return once they train their staff properly and hire more attentive staff. < text>
My Ramen undoubtedly benefits from when people don't want to wait in line for Daikokuya next door, and that's ok!  Nothing wrong with having several good options on the same block.  The special tonkotsu ramen they make here is really good, and the pork gyoza is fantastic as well.  This place should really have a following all its own, regardless of what's happening next door.<//text>

<user>102900955798692058571< /user><user_name>sprintr6</user_name><date>1565657544946<//date><rating>5<//rating><Review>My Ramen Bar is one of the best mom and pop ramen joints in Little Tokyo. Often overlooked by the many nearby offerings, this particular place is one of my favorites because of one thing... their chicken ramen. Ever since my first experience in Japan, I've been searching high and low for a restaurant that could nail the flavor of an otherwise bland ingredient, and My Ramen does not disappoint. To my surprise, I received my bowl within minutes of ordering and the smell brought me right back to the land of the rising sun. Not only was the broth (which takes 20+ hours to create) thick and flavorful but the hearty amount of noodles were cooked perfect al dente. The group I was with also ordered the gyoza, which was singed at all the right places to give it some crunch, and the most unusual appetizer on the menu‚Ä¶ nacho fries which were an unexpected surprise considering the establishment we were at. I mean c‚Äômon, loaded fries AND ramen? How Los Angeles is that?</Review>< Pictures>

Chellee Martin<//Name>
<Text>At the end of a fabulous day walking around DTLA with my lovely friend, it was a great find to have no wait for seating when we dropped into My Ramen Bar. Quick, simple, delicious. The ramen choices are excellent, anything can be done without meat, the kimchi and spring rolls were perfect compliments. And there are a handful of other Ramen toppings on the menu, ranging from dried mushrooms to marinated bamboo shoots, all named in Japanese, that our waiter patiently explained, & each sounded appealing.

He was pleasant and.seemed.amused in  offering enjoyment of the wall screen, which was showing Ancient Aliens. The volume wasn't too loud but I love Ancient Aliens , so it was fun to see the archaeological images flashing on the wall and the occasional audio with its tones of mysterious wonderings on our distant past. The rest of the wall art -big strong black and white brush work of traditional Japanese themes.

Most of all, My Ramen Bar was a great end up for a perfect shared bowl, the atmosphere not too loud, so my friend and I enjoyed a perfect end to our big catch up day.</Text>< UserId.>

<GmapID>0x80c2c60f9fcfbec7:0xa97967e3153c43a8<//GmapID>< review>
Manichi is so underrated compared to its neighboring restaurants with lines out the door!  This place was very calm and quiet, and had very few people inside.  All the better, however, because the waiters were so attentive and always quick to provide anything you need and refill your drinks.  The food was lovely, the ramen hit the spot.  Only thing that slightly bothered me was all the sensationalist claims of having the "best" gyoza and other products.  But everything still tasted great, and I loved the red bowls the ramen came in.  Give it a try!< /review>

< Text>
We arrived promptly at 11 am only to already discover a massive line at Daikokuya, so we decided to take a chance on this place even though it was empty. I'm glad we did! They have delicious black garlic classic ramen, with good pork and tasty eggs available as add on. The gyoza were rich and most on the inside and crunchy on the outside. Service was quick and helpful! I'm no ramen expert but my stomach was very happy after visiting this place.</Text>

<Response>None</Response>< text>
I have to say by far this is the best ramen place I've ever had in LA. Their broth is legit. It comes with black garlic oil and spicy chili oil. According to my friend that I ate with, this is the closest to the ramen in Japan that he has ever had. I haven't been to Japan myself yet so I couldn't say. However, I trust my friends taste because he is usually pretty picky with ramen. I am pretty picky myself, but from my experience this is one of the best.

I normally do not finish all the broth when I eat ramen, but this one I killed it. Do give them a shot.<//text>

<Text>What I Ordered
- Combination: Manichi Special Tonkotsu Shibori Ramen w/ Curry Fried Chicken Bowl
- Spicy Miso Gyoza

I wanted to try the Manichi Special Shrimp Tonkotsu Shibori Ramen but, they were all out of ANY broth with shrimp in it. Not sure if they sold out or they never have it... My friend has been here another time and it was also not available either then. You should probably call before coming if you want anything shrimp flavored.

The Spicy Miso Gyoza was good... just a tad too salty for my liking. I would probably stick with the original next time or skip it all together. Def not the most amazing gyoza I've ever had. The Curry Fried Chicken Bowl smelled a lot better than it tasted. It was just okay. I wasn't a fan of the ramen when I was eating it at the time. It was just meh... but, I scarfed most of it down anyways lol. It was gloomy, cold day and these noodles and soup hit the spot. I had leftovers so I ate that the next day and it tasted so much better! Overall, would give this place another chance ONLY if the shrimp option is available. I wouldn't want leftover ramen for me to enjoy the ramen.<//Text>< pics>

< userid>
111466327454392295616<//userid>
<Text>Was in little Tokyo last night and found this awesome ramen place, it was empty when I walked in so my expectations weren't high. But I was totally wrong not only was the ramen amazing! But the staff including the owner was really welcoming. It felt like I was over a friends house, the owner talked to me for a few minutes and I expressed to him that I was confused and surprised that he didn't have much more business on a Friday night. Of course I knew he was right next to some of the more well known ramen places in LA, but he told me he chose this locations because he wanted to go toe to toe with the big ramen shops. Of course he could've opened up shop somewhere where there isn't much competition and probably started to get a crowd a bit quicker. They've only been open for a year and I hope they thrive because I truly think they deserve to be recognized as a great ramen shop in LA and little Tokyo.

P.s. try there house chili sauce it has an amazing internal heat and pretty smokey flavor. Kind of adds a Latin twist to the ramen!</Text></record>

<date>1431593832297<//date><Rating>5</Rating><review>My friends wanted to go to Daikokuya but the wait was too long. What's so great about it anyway? How about that place up the street with the red neon sign?, says I. The menu impressed me and my expectations rose. Ordered the #2, tonkotsu miso ramen. Then our bowls arrived and my hopes were so far exceeded as to make me question all that I have ever known to be true. Silky noodles with just the right amount of resistance, delectable slices of tender roast pork, a perfectly cooked egg, a pungent squirt of black garlic oil, and above all the deep cloudy glistening richness of the pork bone broth. Presented in Japanese ceramic with a handsome pair of black chopsticks and a ladle of a spoon. Daiko-who? I will definitely be coming back.< /review>< pictures>

< text>
This place has several great things going for it.
Number one: No wait. Compared to its neighbor Daikokuya which has long wait times, Manichi currently has little to no wait time.
Number two: The ramen is great. It had a taste very similar to some ramen I've had in Tokyo, good ramen that is. Basically, this ramen has a flavor I have only tasted in Tokyo before.
Number three: Their spicy miso gyoza are damn delicious. I could eat nothing but these.

Tldr: This place is great. It immediately made it to my top ramen spots in LA list.< /text>

<name>Juvi Guevara<//name>< time>
1426724736307<//time>
<rate>5<//rate><Text>I'm not very big on the ramen scene in LA, but I hear it's all the rage, nowadays,. So instead of going to the overrated & over-crowded ramen houses with terrible service, I decided to give this quaint little place a try. They certainly get points for bravery, opening right next door to one of the more popular ramen shops in Little Tokyo, and maybe even LA.

The ramen here is actually the best I've had anywhere, but again, I'm no expert. The Tonkatsu Bowl with Black Garlic Oil is freakishly amazing slurp-able goodness. The broth itself has a rich, thick texture, and the noodles are perfectly al-dente. Don''t even get me started on those succulent pieces of pork. And the addition of those crunchy bean sprouts and sprinkling of chives is a very nice touch. The best part is that this dish maintains its flavor all the way to the very end; so you may, literally, be licking your bowl clean, just like someone else I won't bother to mention, who seems hell-bent on making a fool of herself. But, I don't care. It was delicious.

The Fried Chicken Bowl is also pretty popular, and not at all bad. After the ramen, it obviously pales in comparison, but it's a really good starter if you're feeling particularly hungry, or are here with a group of people who want to share. It's not very big and comes served on a bed of white rice, sprinkled with chives, so it has a good balance of flavors and textures.

The Japanese vibe here is cool, and the space is large enough to accommodate big groups comfortably, with a long row benches up against both walls and comfy chairs at each table, with a counter towards the end for you singles out there. The service is better than you'll find at a lot of more hyped-up restaurants where they act like they're doing you a favor by taking your money. The people here are really sweet and always attentive, which is a huge plus in my book when going somewhere for the first time and need the in's & out's of the menu.

Even you established ramen connoisseurs out there need to give this place a try. One can never have too much delicious ramen, am I right? Of course I am.</Text><Pics>None< /Pics><Response>None</Response>< GmapID>

< Review>
I've eaten here several times. I keep coming back for more. Sit at a boothe & enjoy cool flavorful, salsa & warm tortilla chips. I look forward to that...
I like their Shredded beef Special Delux Molcajete wet burrito. But you can choose the meat you'd like. Red or, green sauce. Or, both on the same plate. The red sauce has got some great garlic flavor. It'll set you back about $9 add tax & tip. (Price just jumped) Paid $11.45 plus tip today 5/10/2021
Pretty sure it's a husband & wife run business. He prepares, & She serves. Some great flavor coming out of the kitchen. I shouldn't have to pay $16 + tax & tip for that. Shame on Casa Brito down the street. 20 bucks for a burrito?!?! Be a better steward of your own money... go to:
Molcajete Grill 6452 Westminster ave. @ Edwards street 92683 (Update: Last time in, & I got more rice than meat. Buyer beware!)
And, Get your professional, Deep Steam Cleaning done with: CaSteamco.com
Carpet & Upholstery Deep Cleaning. 10% off 1st time clientele. Just ask.<//Review>

<userid>114898773079011299060<//userid><user_name>Kenjiro Yagi< /user_name><Date>1572658487261< /Date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
Thank you Pet Food Express.  I've gotten used to shopping online that I forgot how nice it was to shop and bond together with my dog as we walk around this cozy and clean store designed for us.

My dog and I walked through the sliding doors.  It's not a big store, but both of us were greeted and asked what we are looking for twice.    Everything was well stocked and shelved nicely.  They had every flavor and size of Nulo.  If they had no space for the flavors, they had the flavors interchanged (like instead of having turkey turkey turkey with salmon salmon salmon on bottom, it was like turkey, salmon, turkey, salmon) so it's never hard to grab the one you want.  Small touches like this thinking about the customer gave me a smile.

When I asked a worker a question, she walked all the way to the cash register and back just to get me the answer.

My dog felt so comfortable here.  She's usually in a rush to get out, but was actually sniffing and choosing which bone she wanted from their bone buffet area.

Don't forget!  They offer Buy 3, Get 1 free.  Unfortunately this also means you have to do some math.  Like.. is it better to buy
4lb x 4 (1 free) for $68.97
10lb x 4 (1 free) for $134.97
22lb x 4 (1 free) for $221.97
then you have to consider you can get different recipes, if you have storage for the dog food, will the food expire, what if your dog doesn't like it.... so you might want to have a plan before coming in or you'll be scratching your head in front of the shelf full of food.</Review>

<user_name>Rachel Kirce</user_name><userid>111640625687295916516<//userid><time>1594150400513<//time>< Text>
Measure the dimensions of your unit and get a larger than advertised one if you have items that are exactly the length advertised. I arrived to see it was short nearly a foot on the width, and couldn't fit all my items as a result. They weren't willing to make any adjustments on cost for the fact that they provided less than promised either, so I had to get rid of stuff I would have stored otherwise.

Checked several other units at the place that were advertised as the same size and they all varied in actual dimensions, all smaller by at least half a foot on one side. The contract even says it doesn't have to be the actual size advertised, and I'm guessing this is common in the industry. Nice people, very responsive.</Text>

REPEAT CUSTOMERS OVERCHARGED ON PRICING
I have been a dedicated Extra Space Storage customer at this facility for over four years. Recently I downsized my unit from a 5 x 10 to a 5 x 5.
